<Rate>5< /Rate><review>I have my 6-month check up tomorrow, and I couldn't be happier with my new eyes! I highly recommend this place. It's a very nice office with snacks and drinks everywhere, and exceptionally friendly and caring staff. During the procedure, I felt about as comfortable as you can be because I knew I was in good hands. I'm a bioengineering PhD student, so I had tons of detailed questions (e.g. "so you just removed the flap?", "what is the reason for that device?", etc) and Dr. Pham was able to answer them perfectly while still keeping me at ease. Dr. Darrow is also extremely kind and helpful. My recovery was very fast and I achieved better than 20/20 vision, sooner than they told me I was supposed to. The only downsides are learning not to rub your eyes, some worsened night vision for the first few months, and apparently my contacts used to protect me from crying while cutting onions... <Rate>5< /Rate><Text>I waited a while to write this review just to make sure everything was settled.  I also don‚Äôt usually post reviews online.  But I am so happy with my results!  It‚Äôs been almost a year post-surgery, and my experience with San Diego LASIK Institute, and their Orange County office, has been absolutely top-notch!

I started looking at LASIK options after being told I‚Äôd be a good candidate during an optometry appointment to get new glasses/contacts.  I was also tired of getting constant eye infections from surfing with contacts, and with an active lifestyle didn‚Äôt like wearing glasses.  I didn‚Äôt know where to start so I Googled ‚ÄòSan Diego LASIK‚Äô, found these guys, and made an appointment for my free exam and candidate assessment.

My experience with both offices has been excellent.  I was back and forth from Orange Country and San Diego for work, so I ended up doing my assessment and pre-op stuff in San Diego, getting my surgery in Orange County, and having follow-up appointments at both locations.  The offices communicate with each other, and have been great accommodating my schedule while traveling back and forth.  The staffs are friendly, professional, responsive, and extremely helpful.

Before surgery, I received probably the most thorough eye exam I‚Äôd ever had.  Dr Pham is great!  He had a long discussion with me about options due to my unique eye circumstances.  He recommended I go with the ‚Äòmonovision‚Äô option, correcting just one eye.  It made sense; the goal was to not have to wear any glasses.  My near vision was actually good, despite most of my age group having to now wear ‚Äòreaders‚Äô for looking at anything close up.  It was my far vision that had shifted over the years and needed correction.  I agreed, and they only did surgery on one eye, with the understanding that I could always get it on the other eye later.  This also saved me a lot of money!  Cost was reasonable; they had great financing options and I also went with the lifetime eye maintenance plan.

The surgery itself was unbelievably quick, literally seconds, and I followed doctor‚Äôs orders exactly before and after.  They have a great process that makes you feel comfortable with what they are doing, as it is a bit daunting to mess with the only eyes you‚Äôve got!  Post surgery experience was as advertised; you go home, go to sleep, and wake up with new eyes!  The vision results were immediate and significant.  There are some lifestyle limitations for the first few weeks as you let your eyes heal (swimming, working out, contact sports, etc.), but it‚Äôs well worth it!  I did have to keep my eye lubricated with artificial tears for about 6 months as it tended to get dry (this is normal and expected).  There was also a bit of an adjustment for the monovision over the first few months as my eyes initially fought over which one would focus at about arm‚Äôs length (also normal and expected).  That‚Äôs pretty much resolved now (as they said it would) and I‚Äôm super happy with the results.

My only regret is that I did not do this years ago.  It‚Äôs a significant quality of life improvement not having to worry about contacts or glasses.  My one corrected eye is crystal clear for far vision, holding at better than 20/20.  My brain has adjusted accordingly and the monovision works great for both near and far vision.  Overall I definitely see better than when I had contacts in, or glasses on.  Huge difference surfing, driving, golfing, watching TV, attending concerts/sporting events, etc.  I also really notice the difference at night, things are so much sharper!

I would absolutely recommend the surgery and both/either San Diego and Orange County LASIK Institutes.  They know what they are doing and do it well!!</Text><Pictures>None<//Pictures>< Response>
None</Response>

< Review>
My experience here at San Diego LASIK Institute was amazing! The staff are all great. The office is clean and if you are a fan of snacks, the office has an abundance of options. I definitely felt like appreciated and not as another patient. Dr. Pham makes sure to explain the whole procedure and makes sure that you are comfortable. I got lasik done in the morning and went home and went to sleep, by the time I woke up my vision was near perfect! Dr. Darrow was great with my follow up checkups, she was very friendly like the entire staff at the office. I would definitely recommend anybody who is considering Lasik to this office. You will not be disappointed!< /Review>

< review>
I'm writing this review the morning after my surgery.  The procedure itself was really quick and easy - just be ready for a burning sensation in your eyes while trying to sleep afterwards. One small thing I would recommend is providing melatonin to your patients to help you sleep because the valium didn't really help me. The staff here are phenomenal - they answered all of my questions and provided high quality service.  Not to mention that they have a variety of snacks in each room, even for a healthy eater like myself - continue stocking up on the seaweed snacks because I ate them all!  I highly recommend San Diego Lasik Institute for anyone in the area looking to improve their vision.< /review>

< text>
Posting this on my 1 year anniversary.  Getting LASIK was one of the best experiences of my life and I went with a great institution.  I called to make an appointment then had me in within a week.  Once they cleared me as an ideal candidate we booked an appointment for the surgery day.  Lucky enough someone had cancelled and there was an appointment a few days later - a Friday afternoon no less! Perfect for a couple extra days of rehab (that I didn‚Äôt necessarily need but I appreciated). Should mention they have a lot of ways to finance the surgery.

Surgery day was very relaxing.  A lot of waiting but they hook you up with food and drinks.  The actually surgery took less than 10 minutes and Dr. Pham was warm, scientific, and made sure I was safe.

The surgery is weird but just deal with it.  Dr.Pham walked you thru every step and it makes you feel confident.  (The whole experience is a great party story too).  After surgery, they usher you around, my wife picked me up  and I was home. the next few hours were annoying but just tried to sleep.

Every doctor set up every expectation perfectly.  I knew what to expect and they gave me a solution to deal with it - whether medicine, instructions, outlines.  They were accurate.

I had a check in the next day, the following week, the following month, the following 3, 6 then finally today a year.

I have told everyone to come and you should too.<//text>

<review>I enjoyed my experience getting LASIK eye surgery at the San Diego LASIK Institute. The staff is friendly, and there are always plenty of snacks in the office. For follow-up appointments post-surgery, the receptionists are very easy to talk to and super accommodating when it comes to rescheduling.

Dr. Pham is extremely professional and put me at ease during the procedure. The same-day recovery was probably the only bad part, as you're instructed to sleep as soon as you get home from the procedure, but I woke up in the middle and it felt as if my eyes were burning (thankfully, the pain meds they prescribe you make this go away quickly). Overall, I would recommend this office if you're thinking of getting LASIK. It's been 6 months now and there's been a significant improvement in my vision; working a 40 hour work week staring at a computer screen may negatively affect how much better my vision could be post-surgery, but the change is noticeable and still well worth it.

The best part about my experience getting LASIK would have to be the 0% interest deal they offer with Wells Fargo (so long as you pay a monthly chunk of the full amount of the LASIK cost in under two years, no additional interest or charges will apply). It made getting LASIK affordable and easy, as I only have to worry about a reasonable monthly cost.

Dr. Darrow who I've seen for all my follow-up appointments after surgery with Dr. Pham is super kind too! However, the follow-up appointments seem to last less than 5 minutes each visit as they do an eye exam and shine a light on your eyes every 3-month, 6-month, and 1-year visit. I'm not too sure how effective these appointments are, as they consistently tell me each time that my eyesight is phenomenal but I wonder if the necessary steps would be taken to address any potential issues with my eyes if there were any to arise because these all seem to be pretty routine and once the LASIK is complete, I'm not too sure how much attention and care they can give. Currently, it feels as if my vision is significantly improved overall, but there are times it can get blurry and today's eye exam included in my 6-month follow-up appointment worried me somewhat in that I had slight trouble with reading the letters on the slides, but was still told I had phenomenal vision. Overall, for the price, the bedside manner and skill set of Dr. Pham, and the friendliness of the office staff, it's still worth it to get your LASIK procedure done here.</review><Date>1577414658263<//Date>< UserId.>

1571353497281< /time>
< Rate>
5</Rate>
< Review>
Two years ago I was terrified at the thought of getting Lasik eye surgery, but I honestly had nothing to be scared of. The WHOLE staff at San Diego Lasik Institute are so kind and friendly (shout-out to Theresa, Claire, Brandy, Kristy, Dr. Darrow and Dr. Pham ), and the actually surgery itself wasn't too bad either.

Events I went through:
1) Consultation. Pray that you are eligible for Lasik because it really is a game changer.
2) Pre-op appointment to get your eyeballs scanned and ready for surgery
3) Surgery day! Try to have a friend or family member be available to take you there and back home. If not, they will help you grab an Uber or Lyft.
4) Same day post surgery. Sleep 8 hours. I slept 16 which was the best sleep of my life.
5) Recovery period. DONT TOUCH YOUR EYES! This only lasts 5-7 days but it's crucial! They even give you goggles to ensure you don't!
6) Next day checkup. I was already seeing 20/20 at this time and was well enough to go straight to work afterwards. Having this happen absolutely blew my mind!
7) 2 week checkup. Recovery period went well and happy to report I'm seeing at 20/15 vision!

Getting Lasik was the best investment in myself that I've ever done. No longer do i have to wake up and put contacts in or have to take contacts out before sleeping. And I never EVER have to avoid spicy food again since, well... no contacts

If you're tired of contacts or wearing glasses, do yourself a favor and make the investment in yourself. You won't regret it!<//Review>

<user>104980432284564690036</user>< user_name>
Jonathan Wadley</user_name>
<time>1472421489497</time><rating>4</rating>< Text>
I had a very positive experience getting LASIK surgery here. The doctors are very helpful and answered my long list of questions. They do a lot to alleviate your worries and make you confident that your eyes are in good hands.

It's been a month and a half since the surgery. There has never been any pain and the initial side-effects (halos around lights, dry eyes) have mostly disappeared, months ahead of schedule. I'm glad I got this done and glad I chose this place. My distance vision is great.

I would give this place 5 stars except for one thing. My very near vision was affected significantly. If I try to focus on something that is less than six inches away from my face, I feel woozy. This means I can't put my face close to a mirror. The doctor mentioned that my near vision would be impacted but, I feel, understated the degree of it. This may be unique to me and it might lessen over time, in which case, I'll change this to 5 stars. Knowing this now, I would still choose the surgery. Distance vision is more useful, after all.

Full disclosure: In my follow up visit, they asked me whether I was happy I had had the surgery and, after I said yes, offered me an Amazon gift card for writing this review.<//Text>

<userid>105857900116003721790< /userid>< name>
Rob Marlbrough Jr.<//name>
< Date>
1554928140262< /Date>
<Rate>5<//Rate>< Text>
I've had two different LASIK eye procedures with Dr. Pham, and Dr. Darrow and their team, and they are superb, highly recommended. I had LASIK on only my right eye first (so my other eye could still be used for near/reading vision, to avoid needing reading glasses for normal daily use) about 5 years ago, went amazingly well, zero downtime, went to sleep afterwards and woke up with no pain and seeing great - superb 20/15 distance vision even now.

Then about a year ago I decided to do the left eye as well, because my right eye had adjusted for near/reading use as well, and the left eye was now even worse for distance, requiring contacts or prescription glasses to enjoy movies or TV. The left eye went even better, with the latest in LASIK offering something like 4X better definition in correction, again went to sleep after the procedure and woke up without pain and seeing great, and now I have 20/15 in both eyes, and can still read and see near without reading glasses.

The aftercare and all checkups are included and important to monitor any healing changes and catch even the smallest issues right away. I had zero issues and everything looks great days, a week, months and even years later, the microscopic healing of the eyes went great.

They offer great financing options, and I was able to finance each procedure over 24 months same as cash.

They also offered and may still offer future vision corrections at no charge for a very small added fee, so in another 5 or 10 years, I may get one or both eyes redone if possible, as eyes lose distance naturally as you age.

All in all, nothing to be scared about, painless, financing options, and perfect vision - go in for a free consultation and see if you're a good candidate for what I call bionic vision! :-)

@DowntownRob< /Text>

I left with such a great feeling and was very excited to be on my LASIK journey.

Step 1: Free consultation to see if you're a candidate. Pretty quick and easy.

Step 2: A two-hour appointment to talk about "the scary stuff": complications, money, etc.

Step 3: Decide on financing, schedule the procedure, get LASIK.

I just had mine done and, though I didn't meet him until the day of the procedure, Dr. Pham was friendly, encouraging, and 100% professional. VERY detail oriented. <user_id>108651310750930187509</user_id><Name>Michael Nissan< /Name><time>1500148274849</time><Rating>5< /Rating>< review>
I'm sure everyone gets sick of glasses and contacts, especially when you work on the computer all day. That was the case for me and ever since I heard about LASIK from a friend, I really wanted to get it done for myself. My vision wasn't too bad at -0.5 but I had a bad astigmatism, which made my vision overall terrible. I recently moved to the bay area and looked at practices here for LASIK procedures. However, prices were too high and many practices had a lot of bad reviews. Since I'm originally from San Diego and my parents still lived there, I researched options here and stumbled upon San Diego Lasik Institute. They were the only practice who had a full 5 star rating on yelp and I believe google as well.

Since they are my eyes, I wanted to make sure I'm getting the best quality for the best value. Dr. Pham runs a smart practice in that he focuses solely on Wavefront Lasik (the latest technology out there). This is key to providing the BEST results to patients. I paid around 4k (since there was a discount at the time) in total for the whole procedure and man was it worth every single penny.

A couple weeks after my procedure, I checked in with an optometrist in the bay area and she told me my vision was 20/10 (with both eyes open) and 20/15 on each eye. That was insane, and I believed it, because I've never been able to see so clearly, and so far with contacts/glasses.

My biggest recommendation to people who choose to have the procedure here, please, FOLLOW THE INSTRUCTIONS!

I followed the pre operative and post operative instructions carefully and this led to a MUCH faster recovery time than the majority of patients they see. I checked in with Dr. Darrow a month after my procedure and she told me this was the case. Today, it's been about 7 weeks since my procedure, and I have very little dry eyes (a symptom that takes about 3-6 moths to disappear). After the procedure, get as much rest as you can, and lubricate your eyes as much as possible with the artificial tears. Believe me, your eyes will heal much faster.

Dr. Phams practice has a great staff, especially with Dr. Darrow as his Optometrist. They are more than happy to answer any and all questions you may have about the procedure. I was nervous right before the procedure was done, just as everyone may be.. but Dr. Pham did a great job of giving you the confidence to relax, even just a tad bit. The procedure only took like 10 minutes, it was crazy fast and actually really cool to go through. After the procedure, your sight will be fuzzy but this is normal. But the next day, I was able to see perfectly clearly.

Today, I have pilot vision and couldn't imagine going back. This especially helps since I'm on the computer a lot.<//review>

<Time>1466022444318< /Time><Text>My experience at San Diego LASIK Institute was truly first class and top notch, from beginning to end.  Their office is very clean and professional, with April O'Neil providing snacks and refreshments upon entering.  I initially met with Richard Bloom, who walked me through some tests to ensure I am a good candidate and then watched a 24 minute video which provided some background information about LASIK.  I decided to proceed and booked my second consultation, where I met Dr. Darrow who performed a more thorough test/mapped my eyes.   Dr. Darrow and Richard were able to answer most of my questions, but me being the extremely particular engineer that I am, I insisted scheduling a third consultation so that I could meet the man himself.  The one who would transform my life forever.  And by forever, I mean the last 8 months.

I met with Dr. Pham and brought with me a stack of articles from scientific/health journals, papers, and studies.  I was doing tons of research, reading papers comparing results between Dr. Pham's equipment (both flap maker and actual correcting laser) and other LASIK surgeons' equipment within San Diego.  For everyone's information, the results are nearly negligible, with regards to longevity of results and corrective quality in higher order aberrations, etc.  Dr. Pham spent a significant amount of time from his busy schedule to talk everything over with me, answering all the questions and concerns I had from my research.  In the end, with the equipment being nearly negligible between other LASIK centers, it came down to the surgeon.  I felt very comfortable with Dr. Pham.  Not only was he very compassionate and knowledgeable in his craft, but he is a perfectionist (like me).  And someone I am handing over my sight to, I wanted him to be just that.  (By the way I did see another very popular LASIK center in San Diego.  This wasn't the only one I went to but it was the one I ended up with (clearly))

For those wondering, my personal experience was great.  I didn't feel any discomfort during the surgery, just minor pressure (but not an uncomfortable amount) during the actual surgery.  After I was done, I was able to read the clock on the wall inside of the operating room.  I was SO EXCITED but I wanted to limit the amount my eyes were open since I wanted to ensure a perfect recovery.  So I sealed them shut for the next 10 hours.  I went home that day, went to bed, and woke up at nighttime with 20/20 vision (confirmed the next day).  When I woke up at night, I DID notice halos when staring at the lampposts in my neighborhood.  Those were the only NEW things I noticed.  I noticed starbursts as well but I always noticed those pre-surgery.  Nothing else was noted during nighttime and during daytime, it was crystal clear, no symptoms then.  The following week during my follow-up, my vision improved to 20/15.  A couple months later, the halos were gone.  Since then, I have had absolutely NO symptoms, nighttime OR daytime.  I would recommend being extremely strict on yourself during recovery post surgery.  Use lubricating drops like they are free.  They are cheap enough and your recovery and future symptom-free eyes depend on your discipline.  I think that helped speed my recovery.  I never actually felt dry eyes but I would just use them like crazy anyway.  Why not? I already paid for them ($20 at costco).  If you have any questions on my personal recovery, ask Dr. Darrow.  She knows all about my recovery (Hi Friend!).

I have since recommended multiple friends and coworkers to Dr. Pham and the staff at San Diego LASIK Institute (Hi April!).  My experience couldn't have been any better.  Thank you Dr. Pham and everyone (April) for a pleasant experience.  If anyone has any questions or concerns prior to their surgery or meeting with Dr. Pham, feel free to contact me.  I love helping people out.  Because I am a good person/philanthropist.

Oh also, this message is to Dr. Pham and the San Diego LASIK Institute.  The ONLY thing that I would recommend you guys work on is your WEBSITE.  Out of space, see yelp!<//Text>< resp>

It's a very inviting, no-pressure environment where they show you a video, talk about the day of surgery, and check your eyes to make sure you are a candidate for surgery. Richard, the business manager, does a great job outlining how the process works, the pricing, payment options, and what to expect the day of the procedure.

Dr. Darrow, the optometrist, is a sweetheart. She's got a great disposition and does a good job explaining what to expect after surgery and the vision changes you'll encounter.

Finally, Dr. Pham. He's excellent at what he does and really knows how to get his patients to relax. On the day of surgery, my pupils weren't dilating as quickly as they normally do, even after dilating drops, so Dr. Pham had me hum a song and voila! Dilation. Within minutes the procedure was done and I could already see a difference in my vision.

The entire process from my initial visit to surgery day was about 7-10 days as they want you to be out of your contacts for 7-10 days. I scheduled my procedure on a Friday so that I could go home and just knock out afterwards without  worrying about having to work during the day of recovery. They give you a Xanax half an hour prior to the procedure and let you rest up in a room, then send you home with a Valium for pain relief. I had no issues with pain and no issues with dryness afterwards.

And the cherry atop great results and outstanding customer service? Otis Spunkmeyer cookies and all the great snacks they've got in the lobby and the little viewing area for the videos. ^_^</text>< pictures>

< text>
I first came to San Diego Lasik Institute and Dr. Pham after a coworker had his procedure done with them and gave a good review. When I knew I was finally ready to get the procedure done, I set up 4 consultations around San Diego. I had one with NVision and one with SD Lasik Institute.  After both of those, I had a much better feeling about SD Lasik Institute than NVision and decided to cancel my other consultations and set up my surgery with Dr. Pham.

The consultation was great and everyone there is very nice. As most other reviews note, there are snacks everywhere so if you come hungry, you won't be disappointed.  I had a second appointment  with Dr. Darrow (their optometrist) to check my eyes again since I had been wearing Toric lenses (have to be out of Toric  for 2 weeks leading up to surgery FYI!!) so they wanted to double check my eyes again. Scheduling the surgery was easy and the payment plan and cost are pretty much the same as other places in the area.

On the day of surgery, they give you a Xanax to chill out and check your eyes again before surgery. The surgery was way easier and faster than I thought it would be. There is slight discomfort when they make the flap - more of pressure/discomfort - but no pain whatsoever. Dr. Pham is great and talks you through the whole thing and tells you exactly what he's doing, what you will feel, and how long each step will last. The entire surgery was about 5 minutes long for me. When I got up off the chair, I could see! Everything was completely clear as if I were wearing my contacts. They give you a couple valium, eye drops, and tell you to go home and sleep (pretty easy after 2 valium).

I'm now 2 weeks past my surgery and LOVING the new vision. I haven't had much dry-eye or other noticeable complications. My eyes were fairly uncomfortable for about 6 hours after the surgery but after that, I was good to go.  The day after surgery I was seeing 20/15 which is great!! I'm about to go in for my two-week appointment and am feeling good about my vision so far.

This has been one of the best decisions and investments I've ever made and would highly recommend San Diego Lasik Institute and Dr. Pham!!</text>

Stop looking--you've found the best place to get Laser Eye surgery in San Diego! My experience here has been top notch since the moment I first walked through the door for my free consultation. The front desk staff and Victoria made me feel very comfortable during my check-in and initial screening tests. Everyone who works there is extremely friendly (and in my opinion, good looking which doesn't hurt haha!). And the doctors are straight up PHENOMENAL.

I was referred to NVISION in La Jolla by my optometrist, but I definitely wanted to get at least couple consultations done and do a lot of research. I wasn't able to get a consultation appointment with them for about a month, so I decided to schedule another appointment at SD Lasik Institute as well and got in much quicker. My corneal scans showed some irregularities so Drs. Pham and Darrow recommended I come back a week later after being out of contacts. They determined that I was not a candidate for LASIK but that Dr. Pham would be completely comfortable doing PRK on me. Obviously, that wasn't the news I hoped for because the recovery is much more difficult with PRK.

After going to my second opinion at NVISION, I was told that I was a candidate for LASIK but I got a very weird vibe from that office for multiple reasons. I left that appointment confused--PRK or LASIK?!--so I emailed SD Lasik Institute wanting some clarification about PRK and Dr. Pham called me personally within a couple hours to discuss all my questions in depth! I was so impressed. I still got a third opinion at another place, but ultimately am so thankful I went with my gut instinct and scheduled my surgery with SD LASIK Institute.

Fast forward to surgery day. Dr. Pham made me get dozens of scans of my eyes to send the laser machine--Richard told me that most offices only require 5. Translation: Dr. Pham is extremely thorough and careful. Don't know about you, but that's exactly what I wanted in my eye surgeon haha! During surgery, though I was extremely out of it thanks to the lovely Xanax they gave me, Dr. Pham explained everything as he went. Though I trusted Dr. Pham in my gut before going into surgery, I KNEW I made the right decision when he explained how much corneal scarring I had on my right eye. He went above and beyond to give me a perfect eyeball and said if I had gotten LASIK, the flap would have most likely come off due to the scarring (YIKES!!!).

It has been 2 weeks since surgery and I am feeling great! I still have some discomfort, my vision is continuing to get better and better, and am just extremely overjoyed that I got PRK. I just talked to Dr. Darrow this morning less than 15 minutes after leaving a voicemail.  She's so wonderful and patient.

Lastly, THE SNACKS IN THE OFFICE ARE LEGIT AND AMAZING.  Minor plus :)</text>

Julie Sapienza< /Name>

1456774643828</Date>
< Rate>
1<//Rate>
< Review>
The service was mediocre to say the least....if you have multiple customers in line, don't just stand there and ignore them for a few minutes. Usually when you get called for your order to go they at least ask if you want any ketchup or sauce...nope.
The food was terrible. Ordered a number 1 (famous star meal)...they put so much mayo and ketchup on the burger that the bun was mushy and falling apart before I even fully unwrapped the burger. They didn't even spread out the toppings. One spot had only onions, one spot had only tomatoes and one spot had only pickles. When they did call my order and I asked for ketchup, he gave me a handful...the only problem was the outside of the packets were covered in a syrup-like sticky substance.
Home of the $6 burger....more like home of the mush patty.
I know it's fast food, so I shouldn't expect much. But I was a paying customer. Regardless of what your job is, good customer service should be important.
Won't be eating at Carl's Jr. anymore.< /Review>

< Text>
My first visit to Dr. Robin's office was last month, and I could not be more happy with the results I have now. I had a broken tooth for a while now, and I had been putting off seeing the dentist for months until I couldn't take it anymore. I stopped by on my way driving by, and luckily they were open late enough to see me. He did a root canal right then and there and I have not been in pain since.

I was so satisfied with the results, that I had brought in my mom recently for a consultation. She had not been to the dentist in about 15 years, had ALOT of bad teeth and was very nervous to go in. Dr. Robin was very caring and understanding, and was able to place implants and dentures in only a few visits. Now she is ecstatic with her new teeth and is able to chew into the foods she has missed over the years. He was able to work with her finances, and it also helped that he accepted Carecredit.

If you are looking for a kind, reputable dentist that provides high quality dentalwork, this is the place to go. I plan on definitely recommending him to my family and coworkers!</Text>

<date>1613402411224</date>< Text>
I came in on an emergency visit with a toothache, making an appointment only hours before.  Dr. Marini thoroughly explained the problem, her solution, and what needed to take place before she could remove my wisdom tooth.  My mouth is very small and it was extremely difficult for her instruments to reach my tooth, but she was very gentle and patient, giving me more numbing anesthesia exactly where it needed to go whenever I felt any pain.  Her staff explained very clearly how to stop the bleeding and what I should and shouldn't do throughout the recovery.  In the end, I kept them over an hour past closing time, but had no further bleeding, swelling, or pain and was back to normal life the next day.  My wife and kids had a very different experience having wisdom teeth pulled at another dentist, and I don't think we will try another dentist again.< /Text>

<Review>Where do I begin! Living in Auburn, CA for over 27 years and visited the original owner and location many times. Service, quality, consistently and value were stellar. Several years ago, La Bou changed location and owners; it has been downhill ever since! They were known for their croissants. So many to choose from, but my favorites were the chocolate and the ham & cheese. The croissants were flaky, buttery, large, soft with crisp edges and oh so fresh. I can literally taste it from my memories, however, this is no longer the case. Now, they are missing about half the butter it takes to make fresh croissant dough, the meat is two thin pieces that only fill 25 percent of a corner, and the Swiss is about half a slice. The dough is bread-like, not flaky and it is so dry. The crust was the only sign that butter had ever touched that croissant. Their prices have increased, portions and quality decreased and it resembles nothing like the original locations you find elsewhere. They clearly care more about padding their pockets as much as possible while sacrificing taste and quality at the customer's expense. I honestly have no idea how they are still in business. My review comes after giving them over half a dozen chances over the course of 3 years. It simply doesn't matter who is working, or managing or baking. I have yet to find a good local bakery who does it even close to the original La Bou owners. Save your money and head down the hill to another La Bou or another bakery. It will be worth the trip.<//Review><pics>None< /pics><resp>None</resp><gmap_id>0x809b1ab3ad8a557f:0x2da7a95d7938e7ba</gmap_id></record>

<UserId.>117830591989840119847< /UserId.><gmapID>0x809ada1e8ef9142f:0x1a0107bbd4128c58</gmapID>< Time>
1488784357497<//Time>
<Pics>None<//Pics><text>STAY FAR AWAY FROM THIS PLACE!!!!

The sales people here are lying, deceptive crooks who are ready to rob you of your money in order to make a nice commission for themselves. I came in about a month ago to switch from AT&T, since Verizon had just announced their unlimited plan that I was interested in.

First off, this place isn't even an official Verizon store. They are managed through A Wireless, who is a Verizon re-seller. They are very sneaky at not telling you this.

Rusty helped me throughout the visit, and at first he was great. We told me that I could switch over to Verizon for free and would get a new iPhone 7 if I traded in my old phone. It sounded too good to be true - and it ultimately was. Once I agreed to switch to Verizon and we were filing out paperwork, Rusty told me that the actual cost was going to be closer to $400 to activate the phone. I was really taken a back since he said the cost to activate would be free, but at that point it was too late to cancel. When we were finishing the transaction, Rusty tells me to choose what phone case I wanted. I told him that I didn't need one since I already had a case. He proceeds to tell me that the phone case is free and that it's included in the activation fee. We finished the transaction and I headed home with my new phone.

I got home and looked in my Verizon bag to take out my new phone case. Once I reach in, I realize that Rusty put in a car charger and a battery pack in the bag. "Wow, that was nice of him", I thought. I then decide to look at the receipt and that's when I found out the deception that I had just experienced. It turns out, Rusty charged me $40 for the phone case, $30 for the battery pack, and $30 for the car charger. These accessories, mind you, were the one's that Rusty told me were free. Rusty had also charged me other miscellaneous fee's that he had never told me about.

At this point, I decide to go to the actual Verizon store in Sacramento. The sales crew at the REAL Verizon store were in disbelief that I had been charged $400 for activating a new phone. They looked over the miscellaneous charges and told me that they had no idea what those charged were because the real Verizon doesn't charge those. They said that Verizon only charges the sale's tax for activating a phone, and that the price I should have paid should have been closer to $50. They told me to go back to Diamond wireless and demand a refund.

Knowing this, I went back to Diamond Wireless and wouldn't you know it, Rusty was there. The minute he saw me walking in, his face went white because he knew I had figured out all of the false charges. Rusty was not apologetic whatsoever and went on to tell me that those charges were correct and that they could not refund me. His coworker was especially bad and was laughing and smirking during this whole interaction. The coworker then proceeds to tell me that Diamond Wireless in going to take over Verizon soon, so I "better get used to it". Haha - immature and delusional!

I called Verizon customer service and told them what had happened, and they apologized for the actions and deceptions of Diamond Wireless. They said that Verizon does not endorse the charges that Diamond Wireless charged me for, and that they would refund me for the full amount of the charges. The customer service agent explained that they charged me so many false charges just so that they could get a higher commission. They kindly said that they were going to report Diamond Wireless for their fraudulent activity and thanked me for reporting it.

All in all, do not go to this place if you don't want to get lied to charged unnecessary charges. Do yourself a favor and go to the real Verizon store right down the street.</text></record></dataset><record>

< text>
Had lunch with a friend and have been wanting to eat here for many years now, so glad we finally did!! They are the only place around that offers a Monte Cristo and it was absolutely AMAZING!!

I'm a big, BIG fan of Monte Cristo sandwiches and this one very well may have been the best I've ever had, it was absolutely delicious! It had the taste of high quality ingredients while also feeling the tummy like the best of naughty treats.

I've eaten at Madonna Inn many times and, as usual, the staff are great! Friendly and courteous, very on it every step of the way. The experience of the atmosphere and decor are almost worth the trip alone, you just have to see it to get it.

Copper Cafe also has a huge following for their burgers and my friend said they did not disappoint. It was a very healthy size and she said it was definitely a very high quality and very tasty burger. The fries were top notch too!</text>

< review>
No signs posted for Cafe or Steakhouse anywhere on the Madonna Inn property.  Just follow the aroma from the food.  Entrances are handicap accessible.  Public bathrooms are behind a circular bar with little passage room and then 2 flights of stairs down.  All first floor restrooms were marked for employees.  Food very expensive.  A coffee the size of a tea cup, and a piece of fruit pie was $14.00.  Good service.< /review>

This place is an overpriced gimmick. Came here with the old lady cause she wanted to taste the world famous champagne cake she heard so much. Turns out the recipe she found online tasted way better. I have been making this a destination stop every time I am traveling up the Central Coast. My family and I stop and get cake to go. <Date>1614472056773</Date><Rate>5< /Rate>< text>
They have outside Tent Dining due to Covid. We were still seated next to a large party which made us uncomfortable so we asked to move tables and they allowed us to. The food was just ok. The coke slaw was bad but luckily they took it off the bill.  The salad was not fresh but I didn't want to complain since we already complained about the Cole slaw. The hot sandwiches aren't as I thought they would be..I was invisioning a panini style hot sandwich but instead my turkey sandwich was just turkey on two slices of bread.. not a sandwich at all. The turkey was fresh and delicious and the large scoop of Mashed potatoes that came with it was good as well. Wasn't amazing but it was OK. Husband got the chilli sandwich and liked it. Overall I think the steak dinners and breakfast menu would be better to choose from because this Cafe gave me cafeteria food vibes. Once inside dining resumes I will definitely be putting reservations in for the Dining Room.I give 5 stars because this place is gorgeous and definitely worth the drive. And we always leave with a signature Madonna Inn Glass Cup.<//text>

< UserId.>
112729970998910945119<//UserId.>
<Name>Sherry Talmage</Name>< Date>
1528669168042</Date>
<rating>4< /rating>< Review>
I love stopping at the Madonna Inn when traveling through SLO so I can visit the Copper Cafe! Talk about atmosphere! It has been a favorite spot for me since my first visit at age 8 with my uncle who took me to see their restrooms downstairs! ( A waterwheel 'flushes' the urinal that is designed like a panning slough in the Men's Room! Ladies room has adult and child size toilets with solid wood carved doors for each stall! Lots of hand-painted Italian tiles everywhere!)

The cafe has individual hand-painted murals in each alcove booth where the seats are all tufted red leather and the tabletops are full sheets of copper with hammered symbols along the edge that match the theme of the mural (e.g. crossed pick and shovel for the gold mining mural). Same for the curved copper-topped counter! With red leather stools and hand-tooled copper footplates at each barstool that is intricately designed to follow the theme! The wait staff all dress in period outfits to make you feel you are in a stately Austrian Mountain Lodge.

Their food is delicious and reasonably priced. The sugar on the tables is pink crystals! The water glasses are heavy colored glass (red, purple, pink, blue, green and clear) with a lovely 3-D image of roses. The opulence is rampant everywhere, and is beginning to show it's age, but as they upgrade, they always go for efficiency, classic design, and high-quality. And it doesn't stop there! They have a bakery inside the Copper Cafe with amazing CAKES!

They've toned down the pink and gold that would've made Liberace feel right at home in the main dining room for a more modern feeling of an inside garden party look.</Review>

< Text>
First time eating here. My wife had the Monte Cristo which came with 3 jams/jams (strawberry, boisenberry & apple I believe) and I had the Reuben with fries. My only real gripe was the amount and size of the flies near our original table by the windows where we were seated. Even though we asked to move they were still annoying us and the staff didn't seem to really acknowledge it.< /Text>

[{'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipMKvLHZEbtsIcTRKZzL3nkPfArZOIBYZzMU-F0=w150-h150-k-no-p']}, {'url': ['https://lh5.googleusercontent.com/p/AF1QipPmy3605X4EilTsu4XktGvohLWOB3g6j7iaPDw=w150-h150-k-no-p']}]</Pics>
<Text>Loved it. I've always wanted to visit The Madonna Inn. My husband and I decided to stop on in and I'm so glad we did.
The bakery is right at the front door. Full of cookie and cake goodness.
The wood carving all over is great! The bar area is round and a good size. The restroom, you have to go down some stairs. It was kind of creepy. I wonder where people go if they're in a wheel chair.
All the tables in the cafe have pink napkins and the famous colored goblets. They were so cool. They have them in almost every color of the rainbow.
I ordered the chicken curry soup. It's more like chicken with gravy soup, but it was still good. Not spicy at all. I wanted to get some dessert, so I bought some cookies instead. I got the lemon and the Angel cookies. And the heart cookies sprinkled in pink and in red sprinkle. They were all Sooo good.
After we went and explored the big dining area, which leads to another bar with a huge fireplace and reading chairs. So cool. We went upstairs to the gift shop, bought some things and then headed out.
My husband said well stay next time. So excited about that.
If you are passing through San Luis Opisbo, this is a must stop, even just for a cookie. Look around, take pictures and all that good stuff. Or stay the night in one of their themed rooms. I doubt you'll regret it!!<//Text>< rating>
5</rating>

< Rating>

<text>The food and service were fantastic, but man, is the decor ever dated! I've driven by the Madonna Inn for many years and on a whim, decided to try it. First impression: Like I'd been taken back in time to the '70's. Next impression: VERY nice, polite and helpful staff. Then I was returned to the modern era when their reservation system needed my cell number for a text when my table was ready. I did not see that coming.

Beyond the archaic decor though, everything was fantastic. Our hostess was a sweetheart, our server was spot-on when needed and the food came quickly and was VERY tasty!

Once past the culture shock, this is a very good place to eat! üòã</text>< Pics>

<rate>3< /rate>< Text>
How does one single person get a sandwich and a piece of cake and spent $30? Well that you can do at the Madonna Inn copper Cafe very easily. I had a Monte Cristo sandwich I've had them at Disneyland I've had them at other restaurants and they were amazing this was like eating a limp spaghetti noodle for lack of other words it was very soggy and very messy. I got fruit instead of the French fries and the fruit was the best part of the whole lunch. I also got it piece of the toffee crunch cake back in the older days like a few months ago they used to smother it with toffee shards and on the side there was toffee shards this one here was a little dry there was hardly any cake there was mostly the whipped cream in the middle and hardly any toffee. And for some reason they put almonds on the side crushed almonds on the side not toffee. I don't believe I will go back there for food or even cake it truly wasn't that good</Text>

<resp>None< /resp><date>1503384976400<//date>< UserId.>
101741871043887400347<//UserId.>
< text>
The Madonna is a MUST see location. If you can't afford to stay there or dine in their main restaurant, I recommended giving yourself a nice self guided tour of the place and eat at their coffee shop!

The staff is wonderful and welcoming. Exploring the venue is encouraged! Look at the bright pink main restaurant, bars, dance floor, fireplace, gift shop and don't forget the basement restrooms (a must, trust me)!!!

The coffee shop is like diner food. The food is average and it's pricey for what it is for sure... but it's worth it to sit down and enjoy the scenery. There is a book about the place they sell for $50 but you can bring the restaurant's copy to your table and check it out while you dine. It's super cool. The food is a 3, but the grounds are a 5+, which is why only 4 stars since this review is supposed to just be for the restaurant.

A MUST see!!!</text>

<rate>4</rate><review>Someone said come here for the cake and the cake is what I came here for! Since were in the area and just finished dinner, we decided to come here for dessert. We got the pink champagne cake which was recommend to us and it was really good. The slice is HUGE! Totally shareable among 3 people which we had. The pink champagne cake is a white cake with Bulgarian whip cream filling. The cake was light, fluffy and moist and the whip cream was really good. There was a bunch of while chocolate shavings as well that make the cake super filling. The nice thing was that it wasn't too sweet.

< text>
Waltz into vintage 1958 great American road tripping motor inn and dining bliss. Exceptional service, beautiful quirky atmosphere, excellent meals (tri tip and chicken salad are yummy!) and cake to die for. Find out all about the Maddona family, unique glassware (and purchase one to take home if you like) and the dream come to life that is Maddona Inn. After eating, take a stroll through the complex to small gift shops and a colorful secret garden before you hop back on the highway.  Or spend the night.</text>

< text>
Madonna Inn. Great food. Great service. Fast service. Best cake in the USA. Great drinks. Best Ice Tea. Great breakfast, lunch, and dinner. You cannot go wrong here. This place is what all restaurants wish they could be. The food and ambiance makes this THE place to go in San Luis Obispo County. Note they have 2 restaurants... 1 is the Copper Cafe that is more of an everyday mealtime with incredible food. They also have a more fancy restaurant best for formal dining and date night. Both are AWESOME! Same menu if you ask for it. They also have live bands many nights (blues, jazz, and other softer but sometimes boody shaking music for both young and old).</text>

< Review>
Meh. Arrived at 4pm. Ordered two Madonna burgers, special raviolis, and a steak dinner. The burgers and steak were ordered as medium rare, but arrived well done. The regular fries were way overcooked, but the sweet potato fries were good. Ravioli was not impressive.

<name>Corina Calsing< /name>< date>
1448935666496</date>
<rating>5<//rating>< Review>
Often times, when you return to a place of your youth, the trip only leads to disappointment. Rarely does the  modern incarnation live up to the image in our heads, softened with time.

Returning to the Copper Cafe after nearly fifteen years, I did not have that same reaction. It was great! From the decor to the service to the food, my expectations were met at every turn. If anything, the experience was better.

The corned beef hash is some of the best. And you have got to love the raspberry jam offered. Not just the plane old grape jelly in single-serve containers, but a dish of raspberry jam. Apricot too! The selection of coffee drinks and hot cocoa rival most coffee shops. Make sure to use the pink sugar!

All in all, this place doesn't just rely on gimmick, but on great food and service too. Very much worth the visit.< /Review>

< time>
1477353744816</time>
<user_name>Alan Nelson<//user_name>< UserId.>
118213566834096010375< /UserId.>
<pics>None</pics>< text>
This place is hard to accurately describe... The opulence of Graceland coupled with the decor of a Brothel is probably as good a description as any. In a word, tacky. Actually in two words, VERY tacky but I digress. After your eyes adjust to the dim lighting, they are unapologetically assaulted by the color pink.

As bad as all that was, the food and service made it worth every minute.

There were 15 of us that came on Mothers Day. The place was a zoo but they treated us super! They had our table set up in no time and our waiter was right there taking drink and appetizer orders with a jovial spirit and a big smile. When we got our food orders everyone dug in and enjoyed their choices. I don't remember what everyone had but as usual I of course had the Reuben. It was just right. Tender meat, not too saucy, just enough sauerkraut and bread that wasn't too soggy or hard. I couldn't finish it and I think everyone took something back to the hotel with them.

All-in-all this was a good place to eat, don't be in a hurry, wear some sunglasses and for goodness sake, try the Reuben ;)< /text>

< Review>
This place is hard to accurately describe... The opulence of Graceland coupled with the decor of a Brothel is probably as good a description as any. In a word, tacky. Actually in two words, VERY tacky but I digress. After your eyes adjust to the dim lighting, they are unapologetically assaulted by the color pink.

As bad as all that was, the food and service made it worth every minute.

There were 15 of us that came on Mothers Day. The place was a zoo but they treated us super! When we got our food orders everyone dug in and enjoyed their choices. I don't remember what everyone had but as usual I of course had the Reuben. It was just right. 112245366773772570128< /userid>
<Gmap_id>0x80ecf0e7be1bbf45:0xe0cd9cc95c2a9dbe</Gmap_id>< review>
Great food and service</review>
<Pictures>None</Pictures></record></dataset><record>
<Text>The Madonna and and The Copper Cafe are Icons of San Luis Obispo. They are simply must see and do once, at a minimum. The Copper Cafe is quite touristy, loud and cutesy. From the uniforms of the waitresses, to the never ending wall decor, and the pink, and more pink of the whole place. The menu is simple and straightforward traditional. I have had breakfast here many times, and it is always good. On the last trip it was lunch and the club sandwich was you standard no frills, but has everything club sandwich.
The bakery that is part of the Copper Cafe has the Black Forest Cake, that is a very long standing favorite cake. To view the cake is a joy, and the chocolate on top always gets attention. Walk over and check it out, or notice them on the way in, depending on the door from which you entered.
As is the case for all who visit, tour of the bathrooms is a part of every first time visit. It has been the custom for over fifty years to my knowledge. (my first tour was in 1971)
Next be sure to visit the shops up stairs because they are there and enjoy to overview into the big dining room of the steak house.
If possible a Christmas visit is a joy to see all the decor and decorations.
This is just one of the things you do in San Luis Obispo< /Text>< name>
Stupid Vacations (Stupid Vacations)</name>

< username>
Sally Elbassir</username>
<date>1410987318639<//date><Rating>4<//Rating><review>A friend and I stopped here on our way to Hearst Castle. We were told my multiple people that it's a 'must-see' and I can definitely see why.

The cafe (and I'm sure the actual rooms in the inn) had very ostentatious, medieval style decor. Everything from the pink glasses, napkins, and menus to the carpeting and curtains.

My friend and I split two sandwiches.

Beef BBQ: the beef was thinly sliced and very tender, albeit salty. I personally like salty food, so it was fine with me, but my friend pointed it out. Luckily, some extra BBQ sauce fixed it right up.

Hot sliced roast turkey: now THIS was the standout sandwich. More like an open faced turkey sandwich, it was topped with mashed potatoes and came with a side of gravy and cranberry sauce. It was Thanksgiving on a plate and it was perfect. Order it!

Yes the cafe is a tad on the pricier side for sandwiches, but you're definitely paying for the experience. Great service and friendly staff included! We were sad that we were too full to eat dessert, but there's always next time.</review><pics>None<//pics>< Response>
None</Response>

<Text>I thought this was a tourist trap and a crappy place...I was pleasantly surprised! Anne will be back next time I'm passing through slo. I I had the beef au jus sandwich and it was perfect. Highly recommend.<//Text><pics>None< /pics></record></dataset><record>
<userid>117751903650439005786< /userid>< Pics>
None<//Pics>
<text>The copper Cafe at the Madonna Inn is one of those places in San Luis Obispo that you really should see. The Madonna Inn itself is quite lovely and the grounds are well kept with lots of flowers. The copper Cafe has a  historic old fashioned carved circular wooden bar which is terrific for taking selfies and a good place for  having a party.

We went to lunch with a bunch of friends and had a festive time.  The food is what they call Casual American fare.  My wife had the Monte Cristo, I had the Ruben. Our table-mates had the shrimp Louie that had lots of shrimp, and the turkey club which looked tasty with a big pile of french fries.

We were there for a birthday and they gave the birthday gal a giant piece of chocolate cake, which we passed around among five or six people and everybody got a nice big bite or two.

The truth be known you really do not go here for the food,  it's a fun place for a San Luis Obispo experience.<//text>< GmapID>
